q {
Q:"\\(\\int \\frac{dx}{x^2+9}\\) equals:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(\\frac{1}{3} \\sec^{-1}\\left(\\frac{x}{3}\\right) + c\\)", b) "\\(\\frac{1}{3} \\tan^{-1}\\left(\\frac{x}{3}\\right) + c\\)", c) "\\(\\frac{1}{3} \\cos^{-1}\\left(\\frac{x}{3}\\right) + c\\)", d) "\\(\\frac{1}{9} \\tan^{-1}\\left(\\frac{x}{9}\\right) + c\\)"
R:"Using \\(\\int \\frac{dx}{x^2+a^2} = \\frac{1}{a} \\tan^{-1}\\left(\\frac{x}{a}\\right)\\) where \\(a=3\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\(\\int_{0}^{1/\\sqrt{2}} \\frac{dx}{\\sqrt{1-x^2}}\\) equals:"
A:"c"
O:a) "\\(\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\)", b) "\\(\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\)", c) "\\(\\frac{\\pi}{4}\\)", d) "\\(-\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\)"
R:"Integral is \\([\\sin^{-1} x]_0^{1/\\sqrt{2}} = \\sin^{-1}\\left(\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\right) - 0 = \\frac{\\pi}{4}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The distance between the points \\((2,2)\\) and \\((3,3)\\) is:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(\\sqrt{10}\\)", b) "\\(\\sqrt{2}\\)", c) "\\(\\sqrt{5}\\)", d) "2"
R:"Distance \\(d = \\sqrt{(3-2)^2 + (3-2)^2} = \\sqrt{1+1} = \\sqrt{2}\\)."}

q {
Q:"The lines \\(l_1, l_2\\) with slopes \\(m_1, m_2\\) are perpendicular if:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(m_1 m_2 = -1\\)", b) "\\(m_1 m_2 = 1\\)", c) "\\(m_1 = m_2\\)", d) "\\(m_1 + m_2 = 0\\)"
R:"Condition for perpendicular lines is product of slopes = -1."
}

q {
Q:"The equation of the line bisecting the first and third quadrants is:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(y = x\\)", b) "\\(y = -x\\)", c) "\\(y = a\\)", d) "\\(x = a\\)"
R:"This line makes a 45 degree angle with axes, so slope is 1 and passes through origin."
}

q {
Q:"The perpendicular distance of the line \\(12x + 5y = 7\\) from the origin is:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(\\frac{7}{13}\\)", b) "\\(\\frac{13}{7}\\)", c) "\\(\\frac{17}{13}\\)", d) "\\(\\frac{1}{13}\\)"
R:"Distance formula \\(d = \\frac{|Ax_0 + By_0 + C|}{\\sqrt{A^2+B^2}} = \\frac{|-7|}{\\sqrt{144+25}} = \\frac{7}{13}\\)."
}

q {
Q:"\\((1,2)\\) is in the solution of the inequality:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(2x + y > 8\\)", b) "\\(2x + y \\leq 6\\)", c) "\\(2x - y > 1\\)", d) "\\(2x + 3y < 2\\)"
R:"Check (1,2) in B: \\(2(1)+2 = 4 \\leq 6\\) (True). Others are false."
}

q {
Q:"The equation of the normal to the circle \\(x^2 + y^2 = 25\\) at \\((4,3)\\) is:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(3x - 4y = 0\\)", b) "\\(3x - 4y = 5\\)", c) "\\(4x + 3y = 5\\)", d) "\\(4x + 3y = 25\\)"
R:"The normal passes through the center (0,0) and point (4,3). Slope \\(m = 3/4\\). Eq: \\(y = \\frac{3}{4}x \\Rightarrow 4y = 3x \\Rightarrow 3x - 4y = 0\\)."
}

passage {
text: "Educational planning should aim at meeting the educational needs of the entire population of all age groups. While the traditional structure of education as a three layer hierarchy from the primary stage to the Universities represents the court, we should not overlook the periphery which is equally important. Under modern conditions, workers need to rewind, or renew their enthusiasm, or strike out in a new direction or improve their as much as any university professors. The retired and the aged have their needs as well. Educational planning, in their words, should take care of the needs of every one.\\n\\nOur structure of education have been built up on the assumption that there is a terminal point to education. This basic defect has become all the more harmful today. A UNESCO report entitled 'Learning to be' prepared by edger Faure and others in 1973 asserts that the education of children must prepare the future adult for various forms of self-learning a viably education system of the future should consist of modules with different kinds of functions serving a diversity of constituents. And performance, not the period of study, should be the basis for credentials. The writing is already on the wall.\\n\\nIn view of the fact that the significance of a commitment of lifelong learning and lifetime education is being discussed only a recent year even in educationally advanced countries, the possibility of the idea becoming an integral part of educational thinking in to be a far cry. For, to move in the direction means such more than some simple rearrangement of the present organization of education but a good beginning can be made by developing open university programs for older learners of different categories and introducing extension service in the conventional colleges and schools also these Institutions should learn to cooperate with the numerous community organizations such as libraries, museums, municipal recreational programs, health service etc.."

q {
Q:"What is the main thrust of the author?"
A:"c"
O:a) "Traditional systems should be strengthened", b) "Formal education is more important than non-formal.", c) "One should never cease to learn", d) "It is impossible to meet the needs of everyone"
R:"The passage emphasizes lifelong learning, continuous education beyond traditional schooling, and meeting educational needs at all ages, aligning with the idea that learning never ends."
}

q {
Q:"Which of the following describes the purpose of the author?"
A:"d"O:a) "To criticize the present educational system", b) "The strengthen the present educational practice", c) "To support non-conventional educational organizations", d) "To present a pragmatic point of view"
R:"The author proposes practical steps like open university programs and community cooperation, presenting a realistic, forward-looking perspective rather than mere criticism."
}

q {
Q:"According to the passage, the present education structure assume which of the following?"
A:"c"
O:a) "All people can be educated as per their needs", b) "Present educational planning is very much practical", c) "Education is a onetime process", d) "Simple rearrangement of the present educational system is a must"
R:"The text states: 'Our structure of education have been built up on the assumption that there is a terminal point to education', implying it's viewed as a one-time, finite process."
}

q {
Q:"What should be the measure characteristic of the future educational system?"
A:"d"
O:a) "Different modules with the same function", b) "Same modules for different groups", c) "No modules but standard compulsory program for all", d) "None of these"
R:"The passage mentions 'modules with different kinds of functions serving a diversity of constituents', which contradicts options a, b, and c. Thus, none match perfectly."
}

q {
Q:"According to the author, educational plan should attempt to:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Train the people at the core", b) "Encourage conventional schools and colleges", c) "Decide a terminal point to education", d) "Fulfill the educational needs of everyone"
R:"The opening sentence explicitly states: 'Educational planning should aim at meeting the educational needs of the entire population of all age groups.'"
}
}

meta Subj1:"English"/Chap1:"Grammar & Usage"/Topi1:"Sentence Completion"/Type1:K/Diff1:M/Stem1:"grammar"/

q {
Q:"After years of talking down to his students as if they couldn't understand a word, the teacher finally acknowledged that his attitude was______."
A:"b"
O:a) "colloquial", b) "condescending", c) "professorial", d) "justifiable", e) "logical"
R:"Talking down to others is the definition of being condescending."
}

q {
Q:"There are too many______and not enough serious workers."
A:"d"
O:a) "sycophants", b) "kleptomaniacs", c) "novices", d) "dilettantes", e) "zealots"
R:"A dilettante is someone who cultivates an area of interest, such as the arts, without real commitment or knowledge, contrasting with 'serious workers'."
}

q {
Q:"There was a hint of carelessness about her appearance, as though the cut of her blouse or the fit of her slacks was a matter of______ to her."
A:"c"
O:a) "satisfaction", b) "aesthetics", c) "indifference", d) "significance", e) "controversy"
R:"Carelessness implies a lack of concern, which matches indifference."
}

q {Q:"______ is a virtue."
A:"a"
O:a) "Honesty", b) "An honesty", c) "A honesty", d) "The honesty"
R:"'Honesty' is an abstract noun and does not require an article in this general statement."
}

q {
Q:"His ____ father is eighty years old, and he still runs fast."
A:"d"
O:a) "A", b) "An", c) "The", d) "None"
R:"Possessive 'His' already specifies the noun, so no article is needed."
}

meta Subj1:"English"/Chap1:"Vocabulary & Analogies"/Topi1:"Word Relations & Meanings"/Type1:K/Diff1:E/Stem1:"vocabulary"/

q {
Q:"SPOKE: WHEEL::"
A:"e"
O:a) "square: circle", b) "balance: lever", c) "door: latch", d) "book: shelf", e) "rung: ladder"
R:"A spoke is a part of a wheel. A rung is a part of a ladder. Part-to-whole relationship."
}

q {
Q:"VESSEL: FLEET::"
A:"a"
O:a) "wolf: pack", b) "forest: clearing", c) "vehicle: truck", d) "carriage: horse", e) "squadron: rank"
R:"A vessel is a single unit of a fleet. A wolf is a single unit of a pack."
}

q {
Q:"CALLOW: MATURITY::"
A:"a"
O:a) "incipient: fruition", b) "spoiled: purity", c) "young: old", d) "eager: anxiety"
R:"Callow means lacking maturity. Incipient means in an initial stage, lacking fruition."
}

q {
Q:"CARELESSNESS: ACCIDENT::"
A:"a"
O:a) "assiduity: success", b) "indifference: fruition", c) "care: avoidance", d) "writer: blot"
R:"Carelessness often leads to accidents. Assiduity (diligence) often leads to success."
}

q {
Q:"PERT:"
A:"a"
O:a) "Polite", b) "Deliberate", c) "Moral", d) "Perishable"
R:"Pert means cheeky or impudent. Polite is the closest antonym in social conduct."
}
q {
Q:"PRAISE:"
A:"a"
O:a) "Reproof", b) "Censure", c) "Thymol", d) "Trustworthy"
R:"Reproof is an expression of blame or disapproval, the opposite of praise."
}

q {
Q:"PERTINENT:"
A:"c"
O:a) "Puzzling", b) "Discontented", c) "Irrelevant", d) "Understood"
R:"Pertinent means relevant or applicable. Irrelevant is the direct antonym."
}

q {
Q:"OBLIGATORY:"
A:"b"
O:a) "Friendly", b) "Optional", c) "Facile", d) "Divorced"
R:"Obligatory means required or mandatory. Optional is the antonym."
}

q {
Q:"OBSOLETE:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Desolate", b) "Frightful", c) "Heated", d) "Renovated"
R:"Obsolete means out of date or no longer used. Renovated implies renewed or made new again."
}

q {
Q:"OPTIMUM:"
A:"c"
O:a) "Minimum", b) "Chosen", c) "Worst", d) "Knowledgeable"
R:"Optimum means best or most favorable. Worst is the antonym."
}

meta Subj1:"Intelligence"/Chap1:"Logical Reasoning"/Topi1:"Series & Patterns"/Type1:A/Diff1:M/Stem1:"calculation"/

q {
Q:"28, 25, 5, 21, 18, 5, 14..."
A:"a"
O:a) "11, 5", b) "10, 7", c) "11, 8", d) "5, 10", e) "10, 5"
R:"Pattern: subtract 3, insert 5. 28-3=25, 21-3=18, 14-3=11. Answer: 11, 5."
}

q {
Q:"8, 11, 21, 15, 18, 21, 22..."
A:"a"
O:a) "25, 18", b) "25, 21", c) "25, 29", d) "24, 21", e) "22, 26"
R:"Alternating +3, +0 pattern with 21 repeating every third term. 22+3=25. Next is 18. Answer: 25, 18."
}
q {
Q:"9, 16, 23, 30, 37, 44, 51..."
A:"d"
O:a) "59, 66", b) "56, 62", c) "58, 66", d) "58, 65", e) "54, 61"
R:"Add 7 each time. 51+7=58. Next 58+7=65. Answer: 58, 65."
}

q {
Q:"2, 8, 14, 20, 26, 32, 38..."
A:"b"
O:a) "2, 46", b) "44, 50", c) "42, 48", d) "40, 42", e) "32, 26"
R:"Add 6 each time. 38+6=44. Next 44+6=50. Answer: 44, 50."
}

q {
Q:"Look at this series: F2, __, D8, C16, B32... What number should fill the blank?"
A:"c"
O:a) "A16", b) "G4", c) "E4", d) "E3"
R:"Letters go backwards F, E, D... Numbers double 2, 4, 8... Answer: E4."
}

q {
Q:"Look at this series: 664, 332, 340, 170, __, 89... What number should fill the blank?"
A:"a"
O:a) "85", b) "97", c) "109", d) "178"
R:"Pattern: divide by 2, add 8. 664/2=332. 332+8=340. 340/2=170. 170/2=85. (85+4=89). Answer: 85."
}

q {
Q:"Look at this series: V, VIII, XI, XIV, __, XX... What number should fill the blank?"
A:"d"
O:a) "IX", b) "XXIII", c) "XV", d) "XVII"
R:"Roman numerals increasing by 3 (III). V(5), VIII(8), XI(11), XIV(14). Next is 17 (XVII)."
}

q {
Q:"Look at this series: 70, 71, 76, __, 81, 86, 70, 91... What number should fill the blank?"
A:"c"
O:a) "70", b) "71", c) "80", d) "96"
R:"Pattern: +1, +5, +4, +1, +5... 76+4=80. Then 80+1=81. Answer: 80."
}

q {
Q:"To which industry India's city Ahmedabad is associated?"
A:"a"
O:a) "Cotton Fibre", b) "Poly Fibre", c) "Paper", d) "Textiles"
R:"Ahmedabad is known as the 'Manchester of India' for its cotton textile industry."
}
q {
Q:"'Cork' industry is associated with Cadiz, city of:"
A:"a"
O:a) "Spain", b) "Portugal", c) "Netherlands", d) "Italy"
R:"Cadiz is a city in Spain known for its cork and wine industries."
